<!-- Hero --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="hero">
  <div class="inner">
    <span class="eyebrow">Section 02 · Product</span>
    <h1 class="display">
      From a monthly <span class="accent">promise</span> to a monthly <span class="accent">product</span>.
    </h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The public site today sells a <em>Monthly Growth System</em> delivered by an embedded team. The sprint turned that promise into a repeatable product: five tools, a playbook template, and an operating rhythm anyone on the team can run.
    </p>
  </div>
  <img class="hero-arrow" src="assets/brand-assets/arrow-charcoal.png" alt="">
</section>

<!-- Starting point vs current landing ---------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The shift</span>
      <h2>A service we described → a system we can run.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        The live site talks about <em>"one monthly plan"</em>, <em>"a senior embedded team"</em>, and <em>"zero fluff"</em>. That's the promise. The sprint built the machine that delivers that promise consistently — every month, every client, without relying on heroics from any one operator.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="themes" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;">
      <div class="theme-card t-strategy" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">STARTING POINT · gritfuel.works</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">Monthly Growth System</span>
        <p class="desc">
          Delivered as a service by a senior embedded team. Four-step process: <strong>PLUG IN → ALIGN → EXECUTE → SCALE.</strong> Output is a custom monthly plan per client, anchored in the Monthly Growth System framework.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Promise-shaped · Delivered bespoke · Relies on operator seniority</p>
      </div>

      <div class="theme-card t-product" style="min-height: auto;">
        <div class="accent-bar"></div>
        <span class="num">CURRENT LANDING · this sprint</span>
        <span class="title" style="font-size: 22px;">GritFuel OS</span>
        <p class="desc">
          The first Growth Operating System. Five productized tools + a Monthly Playbook template. Each client runs the same operating rhythm — intake, compounding, escalation, credit allocation, dashboarding — with their own data.
        </p>
        <p class="desc small" style="color: var(--gray);">Product-shaped · Delivered repeatably · Frees operator time for judgement</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <h4>Why this matters</h4>
      <p style="margin:0;">
        The Monthly Growth System is still the IP. GritFuel OS is how we actually run it. One is the <em>language</em> of our promise to the founder; the other is the <em>machinery</em> of how we keep it. We probably need both — the question is which one leads on the public site, and which one sits behind it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Narrative ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: 0;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The operating rhythm</span>
      <h2>Five tools, one monthly loop.</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Each tool owns a step in the monthly cycle. Intake captures the founder's reality; the Growth Dashboard scores where we are; the Compounding Engine picks the next play; the Escalation Router handles exceptions; Credit Allocation sets the spend envelope. The Monthly Playbook is the artefact the founder reads at the end of each cycle.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Key decisions -->
    <div class="section-head" style="margin-top: var(--s-8);">
      <span class="eyebrow">Key decisions</span>
      <h2>What's locked, what's open.</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="decisions">
      <div class="decision locked">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Five-tool architecture — locked</h4>
          <p>Intake, Dashboard, Compounding, Escalation, Credit Allocation. Each has a defined input, output, and owner. Everything else is a feature on top of these five.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Locked</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Client-facing hero: Monthly Playbook, Compounding Growth Dashboard, or both?</h4>
          <p>Two candidates for the #1 artefact a founder sees. <strong>Playbook:</strong> the monthly deliverable — plan, decisions, experiments, next steps. Narrative, warm, ritualistic. <strong>Dashboard:</strong> the always-on view of compounding growth — the tool we actually talk about as the selling point. Live, honest, always there. If the Dashboard <em>is</em> the #1 selling point, then "Playbook-as-hero" is wrong — we'd lead demos, the site, and onboarding with the Dashboard and use the Playbook as the monthly ritual behind it. The third option is both, with clearly separated roles. Needs the four of us.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>How much of the tooling do we expose to clients?</h4>
          <p>Founders will ask. Options: (a) keep tools internal, deliver only the Playbook; (b) expose the Dashboard only; (c) give full portal access. Each has pricing and ops implications.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Does the public site lead with "GritFuel OS" or keep "Monthly Growth System"?</h4>
          <p>"GritFuel OS — the first Growth Operating System" is sharper and more differentiated, but further from the category language founders already know. "Monthly Growth System" is warmer and on-brand with the current site.</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Dashboard metrics — controllables, outcomes, or both layered?</h4>
          <p>Real product-design question. Outcomes the client cares about (revenue growth, customer count, retention) aren't ours to move directly; controllables we drive (pipeline velocity, lead quality, channel mix, content-to-lead ratio) are. If the Dashboard shows only outcomes, we're taking credit for things outside the system's control. If it shows only controllables, we're measuring activity, not value — exactly the anti-pattern founders are escaping.</p>
          <p>Proposal: <strong>three layers, wired together.</strong> (1) <em>Outcome layer</em> — revenue / customer / retention, shown as context, not as our claim. (2) <em>Leading-indicator layer</em> — what we actually move, framed as the bets we're willing to be measured on. (3) <em>Compound Score</em> — 0–100 hero number rolling the leading indicators via the four weighted signals (channel momentum 30% · goal proximity 25% · credit efficiency 25% · dependency sequencing 20%). Plus a <em>connection layer</em> drawing the explicit line from leading indicators to outcomes with the historical lag. That's the honest pitch: "we don't drive revenue — we drive the compounding leading indicators that, over 60–90 days, tend to."</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
      <div class="decision open">
        <div class="marker"></div>
        <div class="body">
          <h4>Escalation Router — human-in-the-loop or automated first?</h4>
          <p>The spec supports both. Starting automated is faster and cheaper; starting with a human-in-loop gives us better training data. Preference?</p>
        </div>
        <span class="status">Open</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Artefacts ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band dark" style="padding-top: var(--s-8); padding-bottom: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <span class="eyebrow">The artefacts</span>
      <h2>GritFuel OS, end to end.</h2>
      <p>Start with the SystemDoc PDF for the full picture. Then click through each of the five tools — they're live HTML, not mockups. The Monthly Playbook Example is what a client gets at the end of a cycle.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="artefacts">

      <!-- SystemDoc PDF -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag pdf">PDF · System Document</span>
        <h3>GritFuel OS — System Document</h3>
        <p class="desc">The complete system overview: architecture, tool-by-tool spec, Monthly Playbook logic, and how the whole thing fits together.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the architecture diagram on page 2 — it's the single best one-page view of how the tools connect.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="downloads/GritFuel_Brandformance_OS.pdf" target="_blank">Open PDF →</a>
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Brandformance_OS_SystemDoc.docx" download>.docx version</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tool 01 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Tool 01</span>
        <h3>Onboarding Intake</h3>
        <p class="desc">How a new founder enters the system. Captures context, goals, assets, constraints — and produces a structured brief the rest of the OS runs off.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the question depth in "Current growth reality" — flag anything that feels too invasive for a first touchpoint.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_01_Onboarding_Intake.html" target="_blank">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tool 02 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Tool 02</span>
        <h3>Growth Dashboard</h3>
        <p class="desc">Where the monthly cycle lives. Scores the founder's growth reality across acquisition, activation, retention, revenue, referral — and flags what the next Playbook should address.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the scoring logic in the sidebar. Challenge the weights — they're first-pass.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_02_Growth_Dashboard.html" target="_blank">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tool 03 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Tool 03</span>
        <h3>Compounding Engine</h3>
        <p class="desc">Picks the next play. Takes the Dashboard's read and proposes a ranked list of plays — each with expected effort, impact, and dependency on prior plays.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the dependency graph — this is where the "compounding" logic actually lives.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_03_Compounding_Engine.html" target="_blank">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tool 04 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Tool 04</span>
        <h3>Escalation Router</h3>
        <p class="desc">Handles the "something broke / something changed" moments mid-cycle. Routes issues to the right operator or flags them for partner review.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the routing rules. The human-in-the-loop question lives here.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_04_Escalation_Router.html" target="_blank">Open tool →</a>
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/Tool_04_Escalation_Logic_Spec.docx" download>Logic spec .docx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tool 05 -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag html">HTML · Tool 05</span>
        <h3>Credit Allocation</h3>
        <p class="desc">The spend envelope. Allocates each cohort's monthly credits across plays, tools, and media — in line with their plan tier (Core / Growth / Performance).</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the tier × category matrix. This is where Finance and Product have to agree.</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn" href="artefacts/Tool_05_Credit_Allocation.html" target="_blank">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Monthly Playbook -->
      <article class="artefact">
        <span class="tag doc">DOCX · Client artefact</span>
        <h3>Monthly Playbook — example</h3>
        <p class="desc">This is what a client gets at the end of a cycle. The narrative translation of everything the OS produced — in a form the founder can actually act on.</p>
        <p class="look"><strong>Look at:</strong> the tone and length. Does it feel like it earns the monthly fee?</p>
        <div class="links">
          <a class="btn ghost" href="downloads/GritFuel_Monthly_Playbook_Example.docx" download>Download .docx</a>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Asks --------------------------------------------------------------- -->
<section class="band" style="padding-top: var(--s-8);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="asks">
      <span class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--lime);">What I need from you</span>
      <h3>Three specific questions on Product.</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Client-facing hero:</strong> is the Compounding Growth Dashboard the #1 artefact a founder sees (and the one we demo / lead the site with), with the Monthly Playbook as the ritual behind it — or is the Playbook the hero with the Dashboard narrative-only? This is upstream of tool exposure.</li>
        <li><strong>Language on the public site:</strong> does "GritFuel OS — the first Growth Operating System" lead, or does "Monthly Growth System" stay as the front door with GritFuel OS sitting behind it as the engine?</li>
        <li><strong>Escalation Router start state:</strong> human-in-the-loop for the first cohort (slower, better data) or automated from day one (faster, rougher)?</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

